\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}

We theoretically investigate charged collective modes in
a two-dimensional conductor with hot electrons
where the instantaneous mode frequencies gradually increase or decrease with time.
We show that the loss compensation or even amplification of the modes may occur.
We apply our theory to two types of collective modes in graphene, the plasmons and the energy waves, which can be probed in optical pump-probe experiments.

\end{abstract}

\maketitle


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:Introduction}

Plasmons in metals, semiconductors, and other solid-state systems have been studied for over half a century.~\cite{Pines1956, Pines1999tql}
Recently plasmonics has found a number of technological applications in chemical sensing, light manipulation, and information processing.~\cite{Atwater2007tpp, Schuller2010pel}
Photoexcitation by ultrashort laser pulses~\cite{MacDonald2008, Baida2011} is one of the methods to generate plasmons. 
When the pulsed excitation is of high enough power,
it can modify material properties of either the plasmonic medium or its electromagnetic environment,
which is the principle underlying the so-caled \textit{active} plasmonics.\cite{MacDonald2008, Hess2012, Stockman2013spp, Seren2015}
For example, photoexcitation-induced population inversion
may permit plasmon loss compensation or amplification.~\cite{Stockman2013spp, Hess2012}
More often, plasmon lifetime remains quite short, e.g., tens of femtoseconds (fs) in noble metals,
which is an obstacle to applications.
In experiments using ultrafast optical pulses,
the plasmon frequency changes with time as the system relaxes back to equilibrium.
However, because of high damping, 
it has been customary to treat plasmonic response of the system as quasi-stationary during the plasmon lifetime.

Recently, graphene has emerged as a new plasmonic medium distinguished by record-high tunability~\cite{Chen2012, Fei2012, Ju2011, Yan2013, Woessner2015} and confinement.~\cite{Jablan2009, Grigorenko2012, Basov2014, GarciadeAbajo2014}


Combating damping remains a challenge;
however, plasmon quality factors as high as $Q \sim 30$ have been
demonstrated~\cite{Woessner2015, Ni2015} for graphene encapsulated in hexagonal boron nitride.
A new scientific frontier in graphene plasmonics is nonlinear~\cite{Cox2014, Cox2015, Mikhailov2014} and nonequilibrium dynamics probed in ultrafast optical experiments.~\cite{Lui2010, Gullans2013, Wagner2014, Brida2013, Tielrooij2013, Jnawali2013, Shi2014} 
Plasmon amplification through stimulated emission~\cite{Rana2008, Dubinov2011,
Apalkov2014, Page2015} and plasmon instability in the presence of a current~\cite{Aryal2015}
have been theoretically proposed.
Real-space aspects of plasmon generation and propagation in response to the optical pumping have been studied.~\cite{Ni2015} 

These encouraging developments motivate us to study the regime
where the plasmon lifetime is comparable or longer than the characteristic relaxation time in a material.
Although this regime may or may not be realizable in graphene,
we consider this as a theoretical possibility.
Previously, collective modes in media undergoing adiabatic evolution have been discussed in theoretical
astrophysics~\cite{Field1965, Ibanez1985, Morton2009}
and cosmology.~\cite{Kofman1994}
In this paper,
we apply similar ideas to solid-state materials,
which are more amenable to controlled experiments.
Our key finding is that loss compensation or even amplification can be a \textit{natural} outcome of the transient plasmon dynamics.

The remainder of the paper is organized as follows.
In Sec.~\ref{sec:qualitative} we review the concept of adiabatic parametric amplification.
In Sec.~\ref{sec:plasmon}, we apply this concept
to plasmons in a two-dimensional (2D) metal such as graphene.
In Sec.~\ref{sec:hydrodynamics} we consider
parametric amplification
of another collective mode in graphene, the energy wave.~\cite{Phan2013, Briskot2015}
This mode is similar to acoustic plasmons (or ``demons''~\cite{Pines1956}) in metals and semiconductors~\cite{Ruvalds1981, Pinczuk1981, Hu1991, Lampin1999, Chaplik2010, Padmanabhan2014}
and to ``cosmic sound'' in the early universe.~\cite{Landau.Fluid, Sunyaev1970, Peebles1970}
In Sec.~\ref{sec:Discussion}
we discuss outstanding challenges to experimental realization of
the proposed effects.
Technical details are discussed in the Appendix.


\section{Qualitative picture of mode amplification}
\label{sec:qualitative}

To model a highly photoexcited system we assume that its electron temperature $T$ is much larger than the lattice temperature $T_l$. Such a hot-electron state typically forms in metals and semiconductor a few tens
of fs after optical pumping.
This rapid thermalization (that is, relaxation of the electron distribution to the Fermi-Dirac form with the temperature $T$)
is due to strong interactions of electrons with each other and with optical phonons.
Subsequently, $T$ gradually decreases toward $T_l$ at a much slower ``cooling'' rate measured in picoseconds (ps), predominantly due to emission of acoustic phonons.
If the plasmon dispersion depends on $T$,
plasmons propagating
in this transient state would have a slowly changing frequency.
We will show that such an adiabatic change of the plasmon frequency could induce parametric amplification of the plasmon amplitude.


